post_text: Constitution Day comes on September 17 of every year. Constitution Day commemorates the formation and signing of the U.S. Constitution by thirty-nine brave men on September 17, 1787, recognising all who, are born in the U.S. or by naturalisation, have become citizens. Constitution Day is a holiday to honour the constitution of a country.

Good news, ECISD teachers!

All-day on September 16, DonorsChoose will be celebrating their 20th anniversary with a funding opportunity to help you get more learning materials. For one day only, all donations to classroom projects will receive a 50% match. This means that a $20 donation will become a $30 donation, a $100 donation will become a $150 donation, and so on.

All you need is a live, approved project to qualify

You can head to DonorsChoose to get started.

We can’t wait to see what exciting ideas you come up with for our students.

post_text:
September is National Suicide Prevention Month. All month, mental health advocates, prevention organizations, survivors, allies, and community members unite to promote suicide prevention awareness. National Suicide Prevention Week is the Monday through Sunday surrounding World Suicide Prevention Day. It’s a time to share resources and stories, as well as promote suicide prevention awareness. World Suicide Prevention Day is September 10. It’s a time to remember those affected by suicide, to raise awareness, and to focus efforts on directing treatment to those who need it most.

#BeThe1To is the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline’s message for National Suicide Prevention Month and beyond, which helps spread the word about actions we can all take to prevent suicide. The Lifeline network and its partners are working to change the conversation from suicide to suicide prevention, to actions that can promote healing, help, and give hope.

https://suicidepreventionlifeline.org/media-resources/

https://guideinc.org/2020/09/01/september-is-national-suicide-prevention-month/

post_text:
Students in Mrs. Gadeke’s class made real world connections with their textbook story this week. Students read about the old practice of hosting “rent” parties where they would play music, sing, dance, and eat lots of good food while donating to their neighbors who were down in their luck. The parties would raise money to help pay rent.

The class connected to the story by building their own harmonicas. While students can’t throw a traditional party while social distancing, they were able to test out their instruments and take them home to perform for their families. #reading #stem #RicebirdPride #NorthsideRocks

post_text: The El Campo ISD school nurses would like to send a huge thank you to El Campo Memorial Hospital for donating supplies to protect our school nurses. Nathan Tudor, CEO of ECMH, donated face shields, N95 masks, and disposable gowns to help our nurses serve the children of El Campo while they attend school. Anita Crisp, director of Mid Coast Medical Clinic delivered the supplies to the school nurses Tuesday morning. Thank you for your generosity and support!

shared_text:
El Campo FFA
July 10 at 9:07 PM ·

El Campo FFA couldn’t be prouder!!!

Ryan Williamson will serve as a Texas FFA Officer for the 20-21 school year.

The primary responsibility of a state FFA officer is to serve. There is no one who has a bigger heart to serve than Ryan!

He will serve along side 11 other individuals to lead the Texas FFA during this next year. The work ethic and drive this young man has makes him the perfect fit for this prestigious leadership position.

Ryan has made Ricebird history and is the 1st ever El Campo State Officer!

We are beyond proud and can’t wait to see what he accomplishes during his year of service.

post_text:
Weight training and conditioning will resume, Tuesday, June 23 for High School Football.

As a public health reminder, staff, and students who are have experienced any of the following symptoms within the last 14 days cannot participate in summer training or other school events:

•Had Cold or Flu-like symptoms (cough, chills, sore throat, muscle pain, headache)

•Shortness of breath

•Repeated shaking with chills

•Had a Temperature of 100⁰ or above

•Loss of taste or smell

•Diarrhea

Known close contact with a person who is lab-confirmed to have COVID-19.

Per UIL guidelines: Any student or staff member living with someone who experiences any of the symptoms of COVID, whether they have a positive COVID test or not, should self isolate for two weeks. If they do not experience any COVID symptoms during that period, they can return to summer workouts.

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.
P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

post_text:
ECHS Announcement

Boys Track, Girls Softball and Volleyball will have an athletic equipment drop off from 4-6pm on Wednesday May 6, 2020.

Boys Track will drop off at the back of the boys field-house.

Girls softball and Volleyball will drop of outside the girls field-house.

Our objective is to turn in all ECISD athletic clothes/ Equipment and clear out lockers while maintaining safe, social distancing.

1. We ask that athletes place all ECISD athletic equipment or clothes in a trash bag or shopping bag.
2. Upon arrival to drop off let the coach know who your child is and the contents of what is being dropped off.
3. Place the bag in the specified box while the coach is taking down your information.
4. If any contents of your child’s locker is needed, allow the other coaches on duty to assist in obtaining those items.
5. Parents will be notified of any missing equipment/ clothes in the future.

Any questions can be emailed to Gcavazos@ecisd.org (Boys Track) or Rcavazos@ecisd.org (Girls Softball and Girls Volleyball)

post_text: We couldn’t let National Library Week pass by without giving a shout out to some of ECISD’s youngest librarians! This year at Hutchins our focus was building better home libraries. As these past few weeks have shown us, home libraries are just as essential as school and public libraries when it comes to building better readers. Thank you to all who helped us create these libraries. Kids received books from activities such as PTO meetings, Family Literacy nights, the Sesame Club RIF parties, a special Christmas gift from community donors, along with the many gifts of books from teachers and family members. Kids, you are doing an awesome job building, maintaining and reading in your home libraries. Keep up the good work and keep reading!

Today, Governor Greg Abbott ordered all schools to remain closed to in-person classes for the rest of the 2019-2020 year. As a result, ECISD will continue its current established Home Instruction Response for Covid-19.

We are thankful and proud of our community. We appreciate all the support we have received from parents, families, community members and local businesses. Together we can see this through. Your continued support and patience during these challenging days is appreciated.

More information about our response can be found at the link below. For other ECISD questions or needs, please contact our Covid Hotline 979-578-8477.

The virus lives in tiny droplets in the lungs of people w/ COVID-19, even when they don’t show symptoms. We can breathe the same air as anyone within abt. 6 ft. of us. Staying farther apart from people during this time reduces the chance of breathing in the virus. #StayHomeTexas

El virus vive en gotas en los pulmones de personas con COVID-19, y a veces no tienen síntomas. Puedes respirar el mismo aire que cualquiera a 6 pies de ti. Mantente más alejado de las personas durante este tiempo para reducir la posibilidad de respirar el virus. #StayHomeTexas

Coughing & sneezing can send tiny infected droplets into the air which can be inhaled by anyone within 6 feet of us. Always cough or sneeze into a tissue or your elbow and immediately wash your hands to lessen the risk of spreading the virus. Be smart. Stay well! #StayHomeTexas

Toser y estornudar puede llevar gotas infectadas al aire, que pueden ser inhaladas por personas que estén a 6 pies de ti. Siempre tosa o estornude en pañuelos desechables o en el codo y lávese las manos para disminuir la propagación del virus. ¡Mantente sano! #StayHomeTexas

Common symptoms of #COVID19 are fever, dry cough, & shortness of breath. If you have mild symptoms, call your doctor & #StayHome. If you develop serious symptoms, such as trouble breathing, pressure in the chest, or bluish lips or face, call your doctor & seek care immediately.

Texas Association for the Gifted & Talented
March 23 at 4:58 PM ·

Who's ready for another Facebook LIVE Session--this time with the fantastic Andi McNair? Join us right here TOMORROW (3/24) at 6 p.m. as Andi shares how parents can help students pursue their passions and make meaningful connections as they learn at home. Learn practical ideas that can be implemented immediately to empower students through meaningful learning experiences during school closures. From Genius Hour at home to daily learning challenges, this Facebook Live will help both parents and educators feel prepared to meet the needs of their learners during this difficult time. Set your calendars to remind you to come back to the TAGT Facebook page at 6 p.m. TOMORROW!

post_text: El Campo ISD is committed to the health and safety of our students and staff. AN AFTERNOON OF THEATER - Come out and support ECHS STARS!
ECHS will host District 25 4A One Act Play Contest on Friday, March 6 in the ECHS Auditorium. Come support the ECHS One Act Play students as they present the award winning play "Pride and Predjudice" by Kate Hammil adapted from the novel by Jane Austen (performed with permission from Dramatists Play Service INC.)

Performances begin at 12 pm. El Campo will be the fifth to perform. The top three plays will advance to Bi-District OAP contest which will be Wednesday, March 18 in La Grange. You can roughly estimate that El Campo will perform around 4pm.

Stafford High School- sf Pipeline

post_text:
The annual TAFE State Convention (Texas Association of Future Educators) was held at the McAllen Convention Center from February 19-22, 2020.
TAFE sponsor, Mrs. Dobie Rod, and seniors Danielle Flores, Jacinda Sanchez, Crissy Flores, and Allayna Fonseca all attended. The students competed with 2 projects; Interactive Bulletin Boards winning a Blue Ribbon for scores in the highest category and Portfolio Notebooks winning a Gold Certificate for scores in the highest category. The seniors were judged on original creativity, lesson planning, and their presentation speeches. Mrs. Rod was also elected to be Vice President for Region 3 TAFE representing the schools in this Region.
“I am so excited to have worked with these future educators and watched them improve from Region to State”.

TAFE sponsor, Mrs. Dobie Rod, and seniors Danielle Flores, Jacinda Sanchez, Crissy Flores, and Allayna Fonseca all attended. The students competed with 2 projects; Interactive Bulletin Boards winning a Blue Ribbon for scores in the highest category and Portfolio Notebooks winning a Gold Certificate for scores in the highest category. The seniors were judged on original creativity, lesson planning, and their presentation speeches. Mrs. Rod was also elected to be Vice President for Region 3 TAFE representing the schools in this Region.
“I am so excited to have worked with these future educators and watched them improve from Region to State”.

SOS at El Campo High School is an interactive science event that that engages the young (K-12) and young at heart in hands-on science experiments and demonstrations. The program will be led by local educators and WIT (Workforce Industry Training) members and is supported by Wharton County Junior College (WCJC), HEB, Aqua Beverage, and South Texas Project Nuclear Operating Company (STPNOC) and City Development Corporation of El Campo.



The program is free to attend and open to the public. Students, parents, educators, and community members are welcome and encouraged to attend.

post_text:
UPDATED INFORMATION

According to Chief Stanphill a non-specific bomb threat was reported to the Wharton Police Department. No specific school or city was mentioned and there is evidence that it is an electronic hoax. We will stay in close contact with ECPD.

****IMPORTANT ANNOUNCEMENT****
At 9:10 a.m. El Campo Middle School received word of a generic bomb threat reported to the Wharton Police Department. No specific school or city was mentioned. In order to keep safety at the forefront, ECMS decided to lock down the school briefly in order to check for any suspicious items. There was nothing found on campus and classes have resumed as normal. ALL ECISD campuses will remain in close contact with El Campo PD.

post_text:
El Campo High School graduate, Ryan Drapela, spoke to Middle School Career And Investigations and Introduction to Agriculture students on Friday.

Many of Drapela’s talents were acquired in his own Middle School Introduction to Agriculture class and his Ag classes in high school. Drapela enjoyed speaking to current students of ECMS Ag teacher, Nick Popp, who is also his former Ag teacher. Students were entertained to see Ryan’s projects, which they are working on now.

“Whether it be making and trying to sell little wooden skateboards in the 3rd grade to making and selling duct tape wallets in middle school or even selling candy to help pay for high school lunches. I have always been looking for something to fill the need of others and myself”, said Drapela.

Drapela recently earned his bachelor’s degree from Texas A&M University. He also earned the title of Entrepreneur of the Year from Texas A&M University's Agriculture School. He runs Drapela Woodworks with 15 employees fulfilling 1,000 orders a week.

ECMS would like to thank Ryan for sharing his experience!

Attention all Myatt Parents! Myatt Elementary is having a Flower & Candy Gram Fundraiser for Valentine’s Day. Please print out the form below to give your Myatt Student or Staff a special treat to be Special Delivered to them in their classes on Valentine’s Day. ANYONE can participate and order for any person located on Myatt Campus – this could be a spouse, parent, grandparent, aunt/uncle, cousin, friend that can give a flower or a candy to be delivered their Valentine at Myatt.
